Short Answer (Interview One-Liner)

Docker does not run Linux containers directly on Windows.
On Windows, Docker runs inside a lightweight Linux VM, so Linux containers still run on Linux.

What actually happens (Step by Step)
Your machine

OS: Windows

Your container

Base image: Linux (e.g. ubuntu, alpine)

How Docker handles this
Windows
 â””â”€â”€ Docker Desktop
       â””â”€â”€ Lightweight Linux VM (WSL2 / Hyper-V)
            â””â”€â”€ Linux kernel
                 â””â”€â”€ Docker containers


So:

Containers still use Linux kernel

Windows just hosts a Linux VM

Why this is necessary

Linux containers need a Linux kernel

Containers are not full VMs

They share the host OS kernel

ğŸ‘‰ Since Windows kernel â‰  Linux kernel
ğŸ‘‰ Docker creates a Linux VM on Windows

On AWS EC2 (Linux)

On EC2:

OS is already Linux

Docker runs directly

No VM needed

